      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The memory leak occurs because you allocate a new `Order` with `new` but never free it, leaving the heap memory occupied until the program exits. You should replace the raw pointer with a `std::unique_ptr` to ensure automatic deallocation. Here is the corrected code using smart pointers:\n\n```cpp\nvoid processOrder(std::unique_ptr<Order> order) {\n    if (!order) return;\n    \n    if (order->type == OrderType::LIMIT) {\n        auto backup = std::make_unique<Order>(*order);\n        executeLimitOrder(backup);\n        // No need to delete backup; unique_ptr handles it when it goes out of scope.\n    }\n    \n    executeMarketOrder(order);\n}\n```\n\nBy passing `std::unique_ptr` by value, ownership is transferred, and the backup object is automatically deleted when `processOrder` finishes, preventing any memory leaks. This is much safer than manual `new` and `delete` management.",
